5. Which herbivorous mammals have homeranges greater than 1,000,000 m? Show only the common name, order, mean homerange size, and mean body mass. Arrange the data in descending order by homerange size and show only the top 10 species.

names(homerange)
##  [1] "taxon"                      "common.name"               
##  [3] "class"                      "order"                     
##  [5] "family"                     "genus"                     
##  [7] "species"                    "primarymethod"

## [21] "preymass"                   "log10.preymass"            
## [23] "PPMR"                       "prey.size.reference"
homerange %>%
  filter(taxon=="mammals",trophic.guild=="herbivore",mean.hra.m2>1000000) %>%  
  select(common.name,order,mean.hra.m2,mean.mass.g) %>% 
  arrange(desc(mean.hra.m2)) %>% #from this step i got top 10 and i found the homerange of number 11 and then filter to show only tope 10
  filter(mean.hra.m2>42065883)

7. Which carnivorous mammals have the largest homeranges?

homerange%>%
  filter(taxon=="mammals",trophic.guild=="carnivore") %>% 
  select(species,mean.hra.m2) %>% 
  slice_max(mean.hra.m2,n=1)

8. Is there a relationship between body mass and homerange size? Make a scatterplot to show this relationship. Be sure to include appropriate labels and a title.

homerange %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x=log10.mass,y=log10.hra))+
  geom_point(mapping=aes(color=log10.mass))+
  geom_smooth(method=lm,se=T,na.rm=T)+
  labs(title = "Homerange size vs Body mass")#Yes,there is a relationship between homerange size and body mass,with larger body mass they need a larger homerange size.
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

9. Use filter to extract the data for only birds and mammals. Then make a plot that compares the homerange sizes of these two groups. Be sure to include appropriate labels and a title.

homerange %>%
  filter(taxon=="mammals"|taxon=="birds") %>%
  select(taxon,mean.hra.m2) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x=taxon,y=mean.hra.m2,color=taxon))+
  geom_point()+
  labs(title = "Homerange sizes(m^2) for Birds and mammals")
